snippet.title: CAM LIVE: Abnormal behaviours and pain with Amber Batson
snippet.description:
Dr Amber Batson returns to CAM to discuss abnormal behaviours that can be associated with pain following her fantastic lives on sleep quality and chronic pain. Abnormal behaviour and pain is a hugely important topic. Recent work from the team at Lincoln University suggests that between 28-82% of clinical behaviourists‚Äô workload may be associated with underlying painful conditions! Amber explains that we must be vigilant for changes in behaviour, because the term ‚Äòabnormal behaviour‚Äô means anything out of the normal for that specific dog. Suggesting that deleterious/abnormal behaviours are only those that fall into specific categories such as repetitive or fear-based, will overlook a myriad presentations that are abnormal for that dog and suggest there is an underlying cause driving them that needs investigating. Amber then goes on to present common abnormal behaviours and the categories into which they fall, giving great case examples of dogs that she has seen. The pair take a tangent and discuss the gut microbiome and emerging evidence of its role in the central nervous system and behaviour. There is so much to learn regarding the biome, but there‚Äôs a lot of speculative material circulating rather than hard clear evidence and Amber clarifies that bold statements regarding what to feed and when are not within reach yet. Finally, the two bring the conversation back to abnormal behaviours and pain and answer a number of questions posed by CAM followers such as whether we should avoid medications so as to preserve the biome, and how to improve communication with your vet. 

CAM is a self funded and self motivated initiative to improve the lives of dogs and their owners. If you feel that you would like to donate and support CAM to continue providing free education please do so here: https://www.justgiving.com/crowdfunding/camhelp

If you just love what you see and hear from CAM and would like to sign up to our newsletter then you can do so here: https://landing.mailerlite.com/webforms/landing/h7p1e

Please support CAM and pop over to our online shop where all profits go back into creating this service: https://www.camonlineshop.com/

Dr Amber Batson graduated from the Royal Veterinary College in 1999. She quickly became very interested in behaviour and undertook a number of qualifications on canine, feline and equine behaviour and welfare. Amber currently works primarily in providing education to owners and professionals in order to improve our understanding of behaviour, both to aid our relationships with animals and also to better recognise and address any health/welfare issues. She feels passionately about bridging the gap between up-to-date science and practical applications of that information.
She also continues to work in clinical practice as a behaviourist and as a vet.

snippet.title: CAM LIVE: Sleep quality and chronic pain Part 2 with Amber Batson
snippet.description:
The amazing Dr Amber Batson returns to complete her conversation with Hannah Capon on the intricacies of sleep quality and how this can influence chronic pain. After a brief recap on the importance of sleep, Amber talks in more detail about the effect of various medications on sleep quality and notes that some medication which is thought to aid sleep actually disrupts sleep patterns. She then moves on to exercise and sleep quality starting with an explanation of the kind of exercise that dogs have evolved to do as scavengers rather than hunters. Their bodies are more suited to longer duration, slower-paced activity and short bursts of high intensity, high speed movement can adversely affect the quality of their sleep. CAM has always been an advocate of good quality sleep and these sessions with Amber explain why it is so important.
